Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.136.249 -p 21,25022,33414,40080 returns the output shown above. By the looks of it, port 25022 is SSH and it is running OpenSSH 8.6. FTP on port 21 is running the application vsftpd 3.0.3; although anonymous access is allowed, there is a timeout when retrieving the directory listing. The applications on the higher ports 33414 and 40080 are serving web applications. The application on port 33414 is using Werkzeug/2.2.3 Python/3.9.13 as the backend. And the application on port 40080 is using Apache httpd 2.4.53. Time to check these applications further. I will enumerate the web applications first.

Enumeration

Port 33414: HTTP

The error message webpage above is displayed for this web application on port 33414.


I performed a basic directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.136.249:33414 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x py,html,txt,zip,sql -d 4 --scan-dir-listings and obtained the two entries shown in the picture above: /help and /info.


While waiting for the full result from the directory search, I decided to check out the http://192.168.136.249:33414/info page. The webpage above was returned to me. This seems to be a File Server application using REST API. Its full name of the application is Python File Server REST API v2.5. The author is Alfredo Moroder. This could be a potential user on the machine. It mentions we can use the /help to get the list of the commands.


Browsing to http://192.168.136.249:33414/help page returns the page shown in the image above. There are a few more available commands: /file-upload to upload files, and /file-list?dir=/tmp to print the listing of the files at tmp. The application on this port allows users to upload files using REST API. The two new commands stand out to me as they could provide me more information about the web server & application.


I checked out the /file-list?dir=/tmp command first, as shown in the picture above. This allows users to check the curent files at the tmp directory. But what if I want to check other directories?


Since this feature can only be used to check what files are available, I decided to check out the /home directory by browsing to http://192.168.136.249:33414/file-list?dir=/home. There is one user called alfredo on the target machine. Next step would be is to check if I can access their SSH keys.


And bingo. I browsed to http://192.168.136.249:33414/file-list?dir=/home/alfredo/.ssh and there are two files: id_rsa and id_rsa.pub as shown in the picture above. This user alfredo has their SSH keys. I was also able to browse to the other directories such as /var/www, but I did not find anything useful. Time to check the other upload feature.


I started burpsuite on my machine to intercept the request & responses of the file upload feature. I made a simple request to http://192.168.136.249:33414/file-upload and intercepted the request. Then I sent this request to the repeater and changed its HTTP method to POST, as shown in the image above. I obtained the message: "message":"No file part in the request". The application requires me to send the file.


On my machine, I created a simple file upload functionality using the requests module offered by Python. I also created a simple file called test.txt that contained the string test. When uploading this, I obtained another error message: {'message': 'No filename part in the request'}. It looks like the API requires two key things from the user: file and filename.


I added the second parameter called filename. Inside this, I had to pass a tuple where the value of the first index is set to None and the second index specifies the path and name of the name. Usually applications like this can be abused to perform path traversal to save the file at certain location. After running it, it mentioned my file was successfully uploaded.


And bingo. My file was successfully saved at /tmp using path traversal with the file name as test.txt. Now I can attempt to overwrite the authorized_keys SSH key of the user alfredo with mine, so I can obtain access as this user on the target machine. On my machine, I generated a new SSH key pair using the command ssh-kegen. The file name I saved it as is alfredo. However, on the target machine, I will need to save it as authorized_keys. I will need to use absolute pathing to specify I wish to save it at /home/alfredo/.ssh/.

Exploitation

SSH Foothold: Overwriting authorized_keys of User Alfredo


I tried to upload the SSH key, but I notice it has a filter in place as it only accepts certain extension files as shown in the error message above. Maybe I can save the key as .txt?


And bingo, it worked. I changed the file extension of .pub to .txt on my machine. Then using my Python code, I managed to successfully upload it at /home/alfredo/.ssh. The key is saved as authorized_keys at this location. Now I can SSH into the target machine as the user alfredo. The Python script I used to upload the SSH key is the following:

import requests

fileName = str(input("Enter filename: "))
location = str(input("Enter location to save: "))

fileToUpload = {
    'file': open(fileName, 'rb'),
    'filename': (None, location),
}

response = requests.post('http://192.168.1.249:33414/file-upload', files=fileToUpload)
print(response.json())

I changed the permission of the SSH key alfredo using the command chmod 400 alfredo on my machine. Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User alfredo to User root via tar Cronjob Wildcard Injection

Checking for cronjobs using the command cat /etc/crontab returns the result shown in the image above. There is a cronjob called /usr/local/bin/backup-flask.sh that is executed every minute.


Checking the content of this script using the command cat /usr/local/bin/backup-flask.sh returns the result shown above. The cronjob is self explanatory. The tar binary is run at /home/alfredo/restapi to create an archive. The output of this is stored at /tmp. The main problem with this script is the wildcard injection used by the tar binary. Basically, we can craft specific filenames that will be interpreted as flags for tar, instead of actual files. Then using the flags, we can execute a script to elevate our privileges, especially if the cronjob is being executed as root. This privilege escalation vector is greatly explained here. We can insert our payload inside the script file; for example, to obtain a reverse shell connection. I will go with my favourite privilege escalation vector: replace the authorized_keys SSH key of user root.


Firstly, I browsed to /home/alfredo/restapi. Then inside this directory, I ran the following commands to create the two flag filenames:

echo "" > '--checkpoint=1'
echo "" > '--checkpoint-action=exec=sh privesc.sh'
echo "" > '--checkpoint=1'
echo "" > '--checkpoint-action=exec=sh privesc.sh'


On my machine, I created a new SSH key pair using the command ssh-keygen. I saved it as root. Then I stored the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIOld2mwyNtN2cxvgx822q85tbp+3vUQ4/2KKAfKAG1Bl kali@kali' > /root/.ssh/authorized_keys inside the privesc.sh file. This command inserts my SSH key at /root/.ssh/ with the file name authorized_keys. It is vital this command is executed where the two other specially crafted flag files are located, as the script privesc.sh with payload will get executed.


Then I changed the permission of the key using the command chmod 400 root on my machine. Afterwards, I connected to the SSH application on the remote machine using the command ssh root@192.168.136.249 -i root -p 25022 . And bingo. Now I have a root shell on the target machine as shown in the image above :)
